Anonymous Thu 18 May 2017 11:38:56 No.9392548 Report
Quoted By: >>9398998
>>9392481
When you say larynx, I suppose you mean pharynx (because the vocal chords aren't the problem here).
The problem is that firstly, their oral (and pharyngeal, not laryngeal) cavity is such that the vowels' formants would be really, really different. Although they could approximate human sounds with this, it would still be what made them sounded very different and awkward.

As for the consonants, those are the killer can of worms: canine and feline muzzles are too different from ours to be able to produce all the consonants similarly.
(Keep in mind, I'm not saying they're not able to speak at all here. I'm saying they would have to have their own language, and that if they were able to approximate our language, their speech would sound really really awkward and weird to us.)
Ask any logopedist, and they will elaborate on how -insanely- important the human tongue is for our speech. (Even truly minute changes in form or function change speech drastically.)
We humans have short, stubby (but as a consequence of that, very quick and agile) tongues. Practically made for speaking.

If canids/felids had evolved a language, it would either have to be fundamentally very different from ours, or their musculature and anatomy would have to change over a million years (as it did with us).

Elephants are dead in the water when it comes to this. Dolphins too, have their own, entirely different way of making sounds (even if they can mimic rough approximations).

Birds are a very good point! However, those birds who can (and this is surprisingly few) mimic complex sounds have entire parts of their brain dedicated to this, and their throats and vocal chords are immensely specialized and deft/agile. They're the best "contestant" in this, to be honest, even thought it's important to remember that the way they make similar-sounding sounds (mimicry) is through different techniques than mammals (which can't do it).
